    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i think i found it. i opened the panel and it looks like the top of the capacitor is actually kind of bulged out and looks a bit swollen? also there's this weird clicking sound coming from inside the electrical box every few seconds. does that sound like a bad capacitor or is there some kind of electrical glitch or something going on in there?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A bulged or swollen capacitor is a strong indication that it's failing and likely the source of the humming sound. The bulging is due to the internal pressure building up as the capacitor's electrolyte breaks down, which is a sign that it's time to replace it. The clicking sound could be related to another issue, such as a relay or a capacitor failing in the compressor's start circuit, which can also cause a humming sound.\n\nBefore you replace the capacitor, it's important to turn off the power to the AC unit to avoid any electrical hazards. Once you've done that, you can safely remove the old capacitor and install a new one. Make sure to follow the manufacturer's instructions for installation, and consider replacing any other capacitors in the unit as well, as they may also be nearing the end of their life.\n\nIf you're not experienced with electrical repairs, or if the clicking sound is accompanied by other strange behavior, it might be safer to call a professional to take a look. Electrical issues can sometimes be interconnected, and a professional can help ensure that your AC unit is repaired properly and safely.",
